In Java, the `foreach` loop is also known as the enhanced `for` loop. It is a convenient way to iterate over arrays or collections in a more concise and readable way.

Here is the basic syntax of the `foreach` loop:
```java
for (datatype variable : collection) {
    // loop body
}
```
The `datatype` specifies the data type of the elements in the collection. The `variable` is the name of a new variable that will be created for each iteration of the loop, which will hold the value of the current element in the collection. The `collection` is the array or collection that you want to iterate over.

Here's an example of how to use the `foreach` loop with an array:
```java
int[] numbers = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5};

for (int num : numbers) {
    System.out.println(num);
}
```
In this example, the `foreach` loop will iterate over each element in the `numbers` array and assign it to the variable `num`. The loop body simply prints out the value of `num` on each iteration.

You can also use the `foreach` loop with collections like `ArrayList` or `LinkedList`:
```java
List<String> names = new ArrayList<>();
names.add("Alice");
names.add("Bob");
names.add("Charlie");

for (String name : names) {
    System.out.println(name);
}
```
In this example, the `foreach` loop iterates over each element in the `names` list and assigns it to the variable `name`. The loop body simply prints out the value of `name` on each iteration.
